section.section:
"Automated external defibrillator (AED)" means a medical heart monitor and defibrillator device that:
Is cleared for market by the federal Food and Drug Administration;
Recognizes the presence or absence of ventricular fibrillation or rapid ventricular tachycardia;
Determines, without intervention by an operator, whether defibrillation should be performed;
On determining that defibrillation should be performed, automatically charges; and
Requires operator intervention to deliver the electrical impulse; or
Automatically continues with delivery of electrical impulse.

text.section:
The EMS Board may:
Adopt regulations for the administration of the Program;
Issue and renew certificates to facilities that meet the requirements of this section;
Deny, suspend, revoke, or refuse to renew the certificate of a registered facility for failure to meet the requirements of this section;
Approve educational and training programs required under this section that:
Are conducted by any private or public entity;
Include training in cardiopulmonary resuscitation and automated external defibrillation; and
May include courses from nationally recognized entities such as the American Heart Association, the American Red Cross, and the National Safety Council;
Approve the protocol for the use of an AED; and
Delegate to the Institute any portion of its authority under this section.

section.section:
This subsection does not apply to:
A jurisdictional emergency medical services operational program;
A licensed commercial ambulance service;
A health care facility as defined in § 19-114 of the Health - General Article; or
A place of business for health care practitioners who are licensed as dentists under Title 4 of the Health Occupations Article or as physicians under Title 14 of the Health Occupations Article and are authorized to use an AED in accordance with that license.

text.section:
To qualify for a certificate a facility shall:
Comply with the written protocol approved by the EMS Board for the use of an AED which includes notification of the emergency medical services system through the use of the 911 universal emergency access number as soon as possible on the use of an AED;
Have established automated external defibrillator maintenance, placement, operation, reporting, and quality improvement procedures as required by the EMS Board;
Maintain each AED and all related equipment and supplies in accordance with the standards established by the device manufacturer and the federal Food and Drug Administration; and
Ensure that each individual who is expected to operate an AED for the registered facility has successfully completed an educational training course and refresher training as required by the EMS Board.

section.section:
Each certificate shall include:
The type of certificate;
The full name and address of the facility;
A unique identification number; and
The dates of issuance and expiration of the certificate.
